Something new is brewing新事物正在酝酿

I created Homebrew nearly 13 years ago out of sheer necessity. I found the tooling available to developers at the time haphazard and difficult to tease into shape. After complaining about it at the pub one evening, I was met with an exasperated “Max, quit whining and do something about it”. So I did. (Thanks Jono).大约 13 年前，出于绝对必要，我创建了 Homebrew。我发现当时可供开发人员使用的工具杂乱无章且难以梳理成型。一天晚上在酒吧抱怨之后，我遇到了一个恼怒的“麦克斯，别抱怨了，做点什么”。所以我做了。 （感谢乔诺）。

From the start, I designed it to be delightful where other tools were not. I have always firmly believed when building anything, especially open source, that the tooling should get out of your way because you have much more important work to be doing.从一开始，我就将它设计得令人愉悦，而其他工具则不然。我一直坚信在构建任何东西时，尤其是开源时，工具应该让开，因为你有更重要的工作要做。

I also intentionally designed it to go viral. I was lazy, you see, in the way all the best developers are. I needed you — all of you — to help me build it. I did this so well that Homebrew became one of the biggest open source projects of all time.我还特意将它设计成病毒式传播。你看，我很懒惰，就像所有最优秀的开发人员一样。我需要你们——你们所有人——来帮助我建立它。我在这方面做得非常好，以至于 Homebrew 成为了有史以来最大的开源项目之一。

Not long after starting, I quit my job to work on this project I felt I was put on the world to make. However… within a few months, the task was long from complete, and I found myself skint. I still remember going to the bank and asking what would happen if I overdrew the next day to pay for rent. They didn’t care much.开始不久后，我辞掉了工作，投入到这个项目中，我觉得我被派上了这个世界。然而……几个月后，任务遥遥无期，我发现自己手足无措。我还记得去银行问如果我第二天透支支付房租会怎样。他们不在乎。

Thus began a steady rotation between jobs and open source. I wanted to work on open source full time, believing it would help the world become a better place. But that remained an elusive dream.因此开始了工作和开源之间的稳定轮换。我想全职从事开源工作，相信这会帮助世界变得更美好。但这仍然是一个难以实现的梦想。

Eventually I burned out and quit maintaining Homebrew. I handed the reins to the community that had emerged from the trail I had laid out. I’m proud to say the project has done very well without me.最终我筋疲力尽并停止维护 Homebrew。我把缰绳交给了从我铺设的道路上出现的社区。我很自豪地说，没有我，这个项目也做得很好。

A few times a year someone would ask me if I would make a brew2. I always said no. What would be the point? brew is good, and I’m not going to reinvent the wheel.一年几次有人会问我是否会制作 brew2。我总是说不。重点是什么？ brew 很好，我不会重新发明轮子。

A Wild Timothy Appears狂野的蒂莫西出现

I met Timothy in Chicago in late 2013. We clicked and worked together on many projects. We were both passionate about what people can build in open environments that encourage and incentivize contribution. Eventually I moved away but the friendship stuck. Timothy caught the wave of crypto while I moved on to become a top mobile developer.2013 年底，我在芝加哥遇到了 Timothy。我们在许多项目上合作愉快。我们都对人们可以在鼓励和激励贡献的开放环境中构建什么充满热情。最终我搬走了，但友谊依然存在。在我成为顶级移动开发人员的过程中，Timothy 抓住了加密货币的浪潮。

Every year or so he’d hit me up and talk to me about what was new in crypto, trying to get me to bite. I always declined. I admired the bitcoin white paper but I felt crypto was just money and, for me, money was the least interesting consequence of work.大约每年他都会打我，和我谈论加密货币中的新事物，试图让我咬一口。我总是拒绝。我很欣赏比特币白皮书，但我觉得加密只是金钱，对我来说，金钱是工作中最不有趣的结果。

A Change of Heart改变心意

My partner and I were trying for a baby last year and in September, she showed me the positive test. We were overjoyed, but the next morning I woke up in a cold sweat. How was I going to provide for my family? Open source was not paying the bills.我和我的伴侣去年和 9 月都在尝试要孩子，她向我展示了阳性测试结果。我们高兴极了，但第二天早上我一身冷汗醒来。我将如何养家糊口？开源没有支付账单。

I went back over all my old ideas looking for a startup idea I could turn into a business. Eventually I came back to my ream of notes about “brew2”. Despite previously snubbing the idea of making another, I am an obsessive note taker and had been recording my thoughts as they came to me for years.我回顾了我所有的旧想法，寻找一个可以变成企业的创业想法。最终我回到了关于“brew2”的大量笔记。尽管之前我对制作另一个的想法嗤之以鼻，但我是一个痴迷的笔记者，多年来一直在记录我的想法。

I moved on, at the time still convinced open source could not pay the bills.我继续前进，当时仍然坚信开源无法支付账单。

Timothy phoned me to catch up and once more pointed me to what he was now calling “web3”.Timothy 打电话让我跟上，并再次向我指出他现在所说的“web3”。

I sniffed around the top of the rabbit hole.我在兔子洞的顶部嗅了嗅。

While learning about web3 I bought and sold a few NFTs. The process was mostly uninteresting except for when I sold one and saw the automated, unavoidable 10% royalty enforced by a digital contract (with no need for a legal structure) that compensated the original creator for secondary sales. I felt the sting of inspiration.在学习 web3 的过程中，我买卖了一些 NFT。这个过程基本上是无趣的，除了当我卖掉一个并看到自动的、不可避免的 10% 版税由数字合同强制执行（不需要法律结构）补偿原始创作者的二次销售。我感到灵感的刺痛。

web3 enables indirect compensation.web3 启用间接补偿。

I wondered if we could apply this concept to helping distribute value to open source.我想知道我们是否可以应用这个概念来帮助向开源分配价值。

I dove down the rabbit hole.我跳进了兔子洞。

The Nebraska Problem内布拉斯加州问题

It’s a well-known problem. Developers make fundamental improvements to the nature of the Internet. Their contributions are grabbed by the community with both hands and inserted into the tower:这是一个众所周知的问题。开发人员对 Internet 的性质进行了根本性的改进。他们的贡献被社区用双手抓住并插入塔中：

Once a block is placed it’s rarely removed. The maintainers become charitable volunteers.一旦放置了一个块，它就很少被移除。维护者成为慈善志愿者。

Solutions like sponsorship and bounties exist. Both unfortunately reward only the top of the tower, the visible packages. Beneath them lie tens of thousands of vital packages that most people don’t even know exist.赞助和赏金等解决方案是存在的。不幸的是，两者都只奖励塔顶可见的包裹。在它们下面是数以万计的重要包裹，大多数人甚至都不知道它们的存在。

Recently Log4J hit the news with a zero day that impacted most of the Internet. They fixed the bug and endured abuse while pointing out that they receive no funding from the myriad of unicorns that use them. They probably still don’t. Most of these hyper profitable corporations didn’t even know that Log4J was a vital brick in their tower of open source built by people they don’t even know and have never even paid.最近，Log4J 的零日事件成为新闻，影响了大部分 Internet。他们修复了这个错误并忍受了虐待，同时指出他们没有从使用他们的无数独角兽那里获得任何资金。他们可能仍然没有。这些超级盈利的公司中的大多数甚至都不知道 Log4J 是他们开源之塔中的一块重要砖块，这些开源之塔是由他们甚至不认识、甚至从未付过钱的人建造的。

CoreJS is another famous example, downloaded 30 million times a week. Their README is depressingly laced with genuine need for funding to help them keep every Node.js application that exists afloat.CoreJS 是另一个著名的例子，每周下载 3000 万次。令人沮丧的是，他们的 README 中确实需要资金来帮助他们维持每一个现有的 Node.js 应用程序。

Let’s Brew a Fresh Pot让我们煮一锅新鲜的锅

Tools like Homebrew lie beneath all development tools, assisting developers to actually get development done. We know the graph of all open source, which means we’re uniquely placed to innovate in interesting and exciting ways. This is exactly what tea will do. We’re taking our knowledge of how to make development more efficient and throwing innovations nobody has ever really considered before. Package managers haven’t been sexy. Until now.像 Homebrew 这样的工具位于所有开发工具之下，帮助开发人员真正完成开发。我们知道所有开源的图表，这意味着我们处于独特的位置，可以以有趣和令人兴奋的方式进行创新。这正是茶的作用。我们正在利用我们关于如何使开发更高效的知识，并提出以前没有人真正考虑过的创新。包管理器并不性感。到目前为止。

Most importantly, we’re moving the package registry on-chain (relax, we’ll use a low-energy proof of stake chain). This has numerous benefits due to the inherent benefits of blockchain technology:最重要的是，我们正在将包注册表移动到链上（放松，我们将使用低能耗的权益证明链）。由于区块链技术的固有优势，这有很多好处：

  • Packages will be immutable (no more left-pad incidents)包将是不可变的（不再有 left-pad 事件）
  • Packages will always be available (we’ll use decentralized storage)包将始终可用（我们将使用去中心化存储）
  • Releases will be signed by the maintainers themselves (rather than a middleman you are told you can trust)发布将由维护者自己签名（而不是你被告知可以信任的中间人）
  • Tools can be built to fundamentally verify the integrity of your app’s open source constitution可以构建工具来从根本上验证您的应用程序的开源宪法的完整性
  • Token can flow through the graphToken 可以在图中流动

Token flowing is where things get really interesting, but first let’s set things straight: we’re not changing the nature of open source. It’s still free. web3 has enabled novel new ways to distribute value, and with our system people who care about the health of the open source ecosystem buy some token and stake it. Periodically, we reward this staking because it is securing our token network. We give a portion of these rewards to the staker and a portion to packages of their choice along with all the dependencies of those packages.令牌流动是事情变得非常有趣的地方，但首先让我们把事情弄清楚：我们并没有改变开源的本质。它仍然是免费的。 web3 启用了新颖的新方式来分配价值，并且通过我们的系统，关心开源生态系统健康的人们购买了一些代币并将其抵押。我们会定期奖励这种质押，因为它保护了我们的代币网络。我们将这些奖励的一部分给予质押者，一部分给予他们选择的包以及这些包的所有依赖项。

Note that no portion goes to us. We’re not like the other app stores.请注意，我们没有任何部分。我们不像其他应用商店。

What is tea?什么是茶？

Founded by Max Howell, the creator of Homebrew and Timothy Lewis, famous web3 evangelist:由 Homebrew 的创始人 Max Howell 和著名的 web3 布道者 Timothy Lewis 创立：

tea is a delightful product suite that you will adore.茶是您会喜欢的令人愉快的产品套件。

tea is the home to a DAO that will ensure the open source maintainers that keep the Internet running are rewarded as they deserve.tea 是 DAO 的所在地，它将确保保持互联网运行的开源维护者得到应有的回报。

tea is our revolution against a failing system.茶是我们对失败系统的革命。
